column20: Light clouds rising to the eastward a hollow moaning sound overheard as if an approaching gale.
At 5 wind fell + very light snow ending in drizzly rain
The aurora in bright arches pale yellow E by S. to W by N.
A streak of the Aurora from E to S to W by N in the zenith and of prismatic colour. At 9 it had disappeared
Bright arches of the aurora from N.N.E. to S.S.W. passing through the zenith affecting the declinometer but slightly
A thick haze on the River
Aurora in a broad arch from S.E. to N.W. pale straw colour.
The Thermometer used for the wet is snow in the air beside two other.
The former, the round glass tube, the two latter on a flat glass scale different from each other 1/4 of a degree and from the round one 1/2 a degree.
Snow during the night about 3ins fallen.
Crust ice driving down the river from west branch and keeping the left bank of Mackenzie .
Quantities of ice driving from the West Branch
Large swapes of ice from the West branch quantities forming in the Mackenzie driving down in the right bank leaving the stream free.
The passage in stream very small from the accumulation of driving ice.
About 2ins of snow fallen during the night
About 12 ins snow fallen during the day
The ice in large quantities driving down over all the river.
Think haze on the River. The ice in large quantities driving down leaving no passage for boats. At 10 it commenced snowing and continued until 1. 30. PM.
Put the glass tube in Declinometer + suspended the needle.

A.M. River not yet fast but all navigation stopped. The needle vibrating very much apparently very sensitive when with any watch in my pocket approaching to read it seems to affect it. Towards the evening getting steady. Its position I think is not good but it is the best I can get.
The needle perfectly steady but at 9 vibrating. At 2 needle steady + 4 vibrating.
Thermometer for the first time down to zero
A bank arising in the West quarter with light clouds driving to the North.
Heavy gale last night snow driving very much. Ice in river not so thick.
All Thermometrical observations perceding this in the air are above zero
A [illegible] arch of Aurora from the Eastward, through the Heavens to the North obscuring the pole. Has + terminating about 10 degrees above the horizon, faint in the centre of arch.
From 2 to 3 ins of snow has fallen to day.
River rising and ice driving slow by ; an indication of soon closing up altogether
River is now closed, forming a very uneven surface
Perhellion on either side of sun subtending an angle of 44 degrees
Bright streaks of of aurora corruscating in the horizon
Placed the needle on the spindle
A faint arch of Aurora extending from E.N.E. to N.S.W. by North the altitude of the centre about 10 degrees.
Show during the night, about 2 in fallen.

At 6 PM a few faint streaks of Aurora to the Northward. 1. Several pale streaks of Aurora to the N.E. extending from S.E. to N.W. in parallel curves up to the zenith. The first and broadest commencing uner many from the horizon passing just under the twins, cutting the tail of the Great Bear and dropping to the horizon. At 7.30 The Aurora appeared and the Declinometer from 16 increased to 30. gradually coming back as the Aurora diminished.
Snow driving fast a dark heavy sky
At 6.15 The gale inoderated and stars shone out, but at 7 it was again as heavy as before.
A pale arch of Aurora E.S.E. + W.N.W. passing through the Zenith
At 6.30 breeze increasing and not a cloud in the heavens
A narrow but double arch of Aurora E by S + W by N peeping directly through the zenith, about 10 degrees above the horizon, to the East very broad
A single but irregular arch of Aurora peeping through the zenith
A thick haze rising from the River
Faint patches of Aurora from N.E. to West; low in the heavens
6 AM Thick haze from the river
8 AM Quicksilver frozen hard with the Thermometer standing between 36 degrees and 37 degrees below zero
More snow fallen last night than at any other time for the season. The wind about 4 morning blowing nearly from N.W. by W
A broken arch of pale Aurora to the north east
Several patches of Aurora in the Zenith
Faint streaks of Aurora to the N.W. and in the zenith
A small quantity of snow fell last night

One of the chronometers stopped last night. The effects of cold I expect, although the the thermometer is not so low as on former occasions, yet with any breeze, even of the lightest it is mst keenly felt
A faint streak of Aurora in the zenith
A faint streak of Aurora in the sky to the N.E. nearing almost to the zenith, affecting the declinometer
Several streaks of Aurora in the sky chiefly in the zenith
Very light snow with several streaks of Aurora in the Zenith
Pale streaks of Aurora to the S.E. and to the westward
A large halo round the moon
A large halo round the moon
A very bright broad halo round the moon, its inner edges of a dark orange colour
A pale streak of Aurora to the north
A large faint circle round the moon
A large circle round the moon. sky hazy
A pale streak of Aurora from S.W. to the zenith
At 8.30 the Northern part of the sky from the zenith to horizon was one blaze of Aurora
prismatic colours broad arches from S.E. to N.W. and bright streaks.
A few streaks of Aurora to the S.E.
The Declinometer vibrating between 106.10 and 105.5, slowly. It lasted for about 10 minutes.
Between 12 and 1, the heavens were compleatly illuminated with Aurora, the Southern half in broad streaks
(horizontal) of intense white light, working round by West, to N.N.E.,
then resolving itself into beautiful prismatic colours, folding + rolling about with a gradual approach to where I stood.
It then dwindled away in bright corruscations, narrow vertical rays, + vanished.
At one time it fairly appeared to touch the vaneof the Fort flag staff. I stood nearly under it + depend upon it,
listedned with all my powers for any noise, but all was quiet. The greatest + most continous body was South of the Zenith,
and during the whole time the Declinometer was greatly agitated. At Midnight it read 105.6'.
When the A.B. commenced it moved to 103.10' vibrating to 103.40. Then 102.30', vibrating to 103.10 and at the brightest when so near, 101.30',
but only for a short time, then gradually getting up to 104.39, when it began to get steady and at 1 AM read 105.30. There was no wind at the time. The Therm. standing at 36 degrees.
A single arch of Aurora from N.E. to S.W.
Bright streaks of Aurora to the North
Aurora very faint and only occasionally. The dip direct 81.54,5
A single arch of Aurora, from E.S.E. to W.N.W.
Aurora to the East in bright flashes of prismatic colours
A large circle roumd the moon and a very faint arch of Aurora from E to W.N.W.
Declinometer vibrating very much throughout the day
Snow drifiting very heavily in the squalls
An Indian came in a starving mate
Faint streaks of Aurora to the North
Snow driving declinometer vibrating very much
N to S faint Aurora to the Northward
Aurora to the N.E. low down and faint
A faint arch of Aurora from E.S.E. to W.N.W.
Aurora from E.N.E. to W.S.W. round by North and nearly to the Zenith coruscating in very bright streaks
A single streak of Aurora to the N.W.
Vibrating very much from North to South
Pale streaks of Aurora to the N.W. low down
Declinometer steady. An arch of Aurora from E to W and passing South of the Zenith, very bright to the E pale strain colour.
A pale arch of Aurora from E.S.E. to W.N.W. peeping North of the Zenith
Declinometer vibrating very much points to S
Much Aurora about 11.15 PM in long and irregular narrow belts low down
from East to West broken arches half way to the zenith where it became very faint
11.20 It resolved itself into flashes and corruscating of extreme brilliancy both horizontal and vertical
settling between North and W.N.W. extending over a space of about forty degrees from a very low altitude.
The glass shewy bright through it. At midnight it was very light. The declinometer was hardly affected. The dip at the time, Direct and Face East 82.10' and 82.15'
A very heavy fall of snow last night and now continuing thick. A fall of about 10 ins
A very heavy fall of snow last night, from 7 to 8 ins
A faint arch of Aurora low down to the Northward
Snow driving and declinometer vibrating very much
Aurora in the Zenith, faint streaks
A faint arch of Aurora to the Northward
Aurora from E to W in a pale uneven arch
Faint rays of Aurora to the East and in the zenith continually through the clouds
A pale broken arch of Aurora to the N.W.
A double arch of Aurora from E.S.E. to W.N.W. very pale
Wild fowl seen to day, one goose and two ducks
At 5:30 the River Liard made a move
A faint arch of Aurora passing through the zenith from E.S.E. to W.N.W.
Ice moving in large masses in the Mackenzie
6. Ice moving in the stream in the Mackenzie
Ice moving off fast in the Mackenzie from the Liard
At 6.45 the wind came up strong from N.W. in a heavy squall, the Declinometer vibrating very much
A light fall of snow last night
Very light showers of snow, occasionally
The Mackenzie ice moved this morning
6. Much Ice passing down the River
Mr. Hooper and party arrived from Bear Lake
Passing showers at intervals all day
at 2 PM very heavy rain with heavy thunder
The sun set in heavy clouds and blood red
